### Tested versions

- Reproducible in v4.5 double precision mono build [a210fe6db]

### System information

v4.5.dev.mono.double.custom_build [a210fe6db]

### Issue description

The Object (where Node comes from) _Notification virtual function expects a 32 bit integer as `what` parameter.
However, the build-in Notifications like NotificationReady is declared as long.

We can cast the long to a int32, but this is not good practice for low level stuff like this.
```cs
public override void _Notification(int what)
    {
        switch (what)
        {
            case NotificationReady:
                break;
            default:
                break;
        }
    }
```

![Image](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/88de2a88-d3ca-48b8-9a46-0bc7fab9ad45)

I think the root cause is that the binding generator is overly aggressive in promoting integer types to 64-bit (long) for C# compatibility, likely to match the int64_t expectation in ptrcall. However, this doesn’t align with the actual C++ signature of _notification(int p_notification), which remains 32-bit. The generator doesn’t distinguish between method parameters (which should stay int for _notification) and constants (which it forces to long).

### Steps to reproduce

Build the engine with dotnet and with double precision enabled 
Open editor, start new project
Add Node to scene
Add C# script to node with following _Notification() override function:
```
public override void _Notification(int what)
    {
        switch (what)
        {
            case NotificationReady: // <-- needs (int) casting. Bad!
                break;
            default:
                break;
        }
    }
```

